g of controversial reforms. Newton’s analysis reveals how rival descriptions of immigrant groups and the flattering or disparaging myths that surround them define, shape, and can ultimately determine fights over immigration policy. Her pathbreaking findings will shed new light on the current political battles, their likely outcomes, and where to go from here.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh  a1980s.  a1990s.  aBeginning.  aLina.  aNewton.  aclose.  acontroversial.  adisputes.  afrom.  aillegal.  aimmigrants.  aintroduction.  alegislators.  alook.  anegativefacilitated.  aoverwhelmingly.  apassing.  aportrayals.  apositive.  areforms.  areveals.  ashift.  awith.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081475842740uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814759028.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814759028/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK